r a handful of emeralds.  They stood before the Dragon of Hate, as Payle had requested.  Selilya's eyes seemed to study the gaunt, bedraggled woman before her, while feeling the weight of the emeralds in her hand.  She said simply, &quot;This is  harsh, you know...&quot;<br>
Payle could only answer, &quot;Innoruuk demands it.&quot;<br>
Selilya nodded.  Her face clouded until it was an expressionless mask.  It seemed to Payle, that this might be the way in which Selilya removed herself from the task that she must now perform.  <br>
Payle knelt before the Dragon, and the Winnower, and kissed the cool stone of the floor.  She was soul-tired.  She still keenly felt the displeasure of her god.  She had survived his punishment, if only just.  It was up to her now, to sacrifice and atone, to begin to set things as they should always have been.  And what better sacrifice to make, than to trade her own life's essence for emeralds imbued with the power to grant life again to others, those she truly cared about.<br>
&quot;You are ready?&quot;, asked the Winnower.  It sounded more like a reassurance, than a question.<br>
Payle nodded once, then steeled herself.  She held one image in her mind's eye, that of the perfect world she had been shown in her vision, as she marshalled all of the self-discipline she had ever learned.<br>
Selilya began to chant.  At a point, her soul asked Payle's for permission to continue.  Gratefully, Payle accepted, and she soon felt the first magical ebb, as her life force drained away and into a now glowing stone.  Surprisingly, there was no pain, only relief, and a growing emptiness.<br>
The Winnower continued, each time asking her permission.  Each time, Payle readily agreed, and felt more of her vitality sucked from her, and channeled by Selilya into a handful of irradiant emeralds, seven in all.<br>
It did not take long, and when it was finished, both women seemed reluctant to move.  Payle felt weak and somewhat disoriented, but most importantly she felt completely voided, like a newly forged vessel.  And she felt in the heart of her soul, that Innorruuk was pleased with her sacrifice.  She struggled to find the words to communicate to Selilya, her gratitude.  <br>
&quot;Thank you , my Winnower, for you are truly an instrument of Innoruuk.&quot;  She bowed deeply.<br>
&quot;Innoruuk will bless you for this, Payle&quot;, she said, and smiled.<br>
&quot;He already has...&quot;  Payle returned the smile.<br>
The two women sat before the Dragon of Hate for a long while, in near silence, and long after the Winnower left to attend to other duties, Payle continued to sit, in silence and meditation.  She thanked Innorruuk for this trial, and prayed that only the grace of his purest Hate would fill her now.  She prayed also for the strength to truly forgive herself.  No longer would she let self-hatred and doubt consume her, distract her.  She rose, and saluted the Dragon of Hate.  <br>
&quot;Use me as you will.&quot;<br>
